            "type": "paragraph",
            "content": "While most Casas Adobes solar installations operate without battery storage (relying on TEP's excellent net metering as free virtual battery), some homeowners add batteries for backup power or increased independence. Battery storage basics: Store excess daytime production for evening use or outages, provide backup when grid fails (standard solar shuts down during outages for safety), enable time-of-use optimization, increase utility independence. Leading battery options: Tesla Powerwall 2 (13.5 kWh usable, proven reliability, integrated inverter, smartphone monitoring), Enphase IQ Battery (modular 3.36-10.08 kWh, works with Enphase microinverters, scalable), LG RESU (9.8-16 kWh, excellent warranty, proven performance), Generac PWRcell (9-18 kWh modular design, American manufacturing, strong warranty). Typical configurations: Essential loads backup (10-13 kWh) powers refrigerator, lights, internet, garage door, select circuits, adequate for critical needs. Partial home backup (17-20 kWh) adds AC for 1-2 rooms, outlets, washer/dryer, expanded coverage, comfortable during extended outages. Whole-home backup (27-40+ kWh) powers entire home including complete HVAC, all appliances, normal lifestyle, requires multiple batteries and substantial investment. Battery economics: Unlike solar with clear 7-10 year payback, batteries rarely pay for themselves through arbitrage alone in TEP territory due to excellent net metering. Costs: $10,000-$15,000 (10-13 kWh) to $25,000-$45,000+ (whole-home), with 30% federal tax credit applying. When batteries make sense: Frequent power outages in your Casas Adobes area, critical medical equipment needing uninterrupted power, home business where outages cause income loss, time-of-use rates if TEP eliminates net metering, complete energy independence priority beyond economics. When they don't: Rare outages (1-2 annually, few hours), no critical power needs justifying $10,000-$20,000+ investment, existing whole-home generator, prioritizing maximum solar ROI over independence. Our recommendation: Most Casas Adobes solar customers should install solar without batteries initially, taking advantage of excellent net metering while available, considering batteries later if TEP changes policies, outage frequency increases, or circumstances change (medical equipment, home business). Batteries can be added to existing systems - you're not locked in at installation. We provide honest battery consultations evaluating specific needs, outage history, critical loads, financial priorities, never pressuring toward expensive batteries when solar alone makes more financial sense."
